I have s24 ultra and iphone 15 pro, and I noticed I like using s24 ultra more, the screen is so great for watching videos and reading ebooks, and the new AR coating is fantastic, it feels like reading a ereader.

Update on the S24 Ultra vs S25 Ultra

S24 Ultra
- Box Style shape (Just like the original note series)
- S24 Ultra first flat screen with eligant curved frame gives premium style (Flat screen protector frienldy)
- Brightness was tested as ive seen and notice is brighter. (Coating or what not probably causing this but the anti reflection is nearly identical)
- S-Pen bluetooth (Gimick or useful but still very nice knowing you have some inspector gadget type tech in your pocket if needed)
- One UI 7 Update for the S24U has some new video exporting blowing away the non optimized version of the S25 U as seen and tested.
- Camera rings are solid and premium (Flush no potential removal)
- 7 years of update (S24U) and was originally advertised as the AI phone already (I use all the AI features Minus the Now brief on the S25 Ultra i had it turned off)
- S-pen location on the S24 Ultra is in a perfect spot for cases (S25 Ultra seems to have it in a odd location where its curved so all the cases have a nasty open cutout in the corner)

S25 Ultra
- Feels like an Iphone which i always envyed iphone users having a flat square display but the samsung design lost its touch reminds me of the redmagic phone (not Note shape)
- Faster CPU but samsung is behind updating a more optimized version for the S25 Ultra
- Nearly only one year extra of uptades vs the S24 U 
- Extra pixels in one camera (I dont see the difference)
- Blue tooth 5.4 vs 5.3 (Dont notice much maybe the 6.0 will be a bigger upgrade.


Conclusion:
Sending my S25 Ultra back and will continue to use the S24 Ultra (I will snag a new one when they come back to the Note roots i have  under 7 years not in a hurry but ill cross my fingers on this one)

One thing I noticed is the battery management is absolutely amazing. Where I would run out 15% of my battery, I now run 1-2% max, it's actually insane...
Yes my S21 Ultra was getting old and I used it A LOT, so the battery would have been losing efficiency. But my god, that's 7x+ on the top end, I don't think i've ever had that experience when i've upgraded, and i've gone
S2 > S4 > S7 Edge > S9 Plus > S21 Ultra > Now this.
Not a single one of those upgrades gave me this battery efficiency.

This comment is important.  DO NOT BUY ANY SAMSUNG DEVICE. Samsung updates will randomly give your device a green line. Do not listen to them saying it's damage, because I had multiple devices develop the line simultaneously,  no damage, some in box, and these are multiple generations of devices. The only common factor, an update. Samsung refuses to fix the issue, even denying they've had reports if thus, although there are hundreds of thousands facing this issue, if not more. There are reports on their own help forum, but they deny. You will be asked to return it to a Samsung repair center, if you live in a country that has these, and you will be charged a fee if your device is older than 1 year. This fee does not cover repairs. They will want to replace the screen, but the issue will eventually return because it's a software defect. I trust you know a new screen is almost the cost of the device. Note, even if you are in warranty,  you're not covered. Fingernail scratches are considered user damage, but tempered screen protectors are also considered damage because they use adhesive.  I have never seen that adhesive  damage a screen. Essentially,  they're damaging your device with an update you gave no choice in installing,  then will charge you to repair it. It is a cash grab that should face a class action  lawsuit.  Note that this is not based solely on my experience,rather, it is the common experience of those who encounter this problem and reach out to Samsung for help.

Something everyone misses about screen saturation on the S24s is that by default the saturation slider is set to the lowest. Go into settings>display>adaptive colour tone and turn it off. Then go into screen mode, select "vivid" then the "advanced settings" button. You will get a 3 step slider. By default it is set to the lowest. I have mine in the middle. But if you like the old samsung overly saturated look, you can get it by sliding it to the max. The screen is amazing either way. And then you CAN turn adaptive colour tone back on.
The saturation problem was a bug. They added the vividness slider with an update and fixed it.

I have purchased Samsung phones exclusively since cell phones came on the scene. My current phone is the Z Fold 4; however, that phone became virtually unusable when it suffered from what I understand is a not so uncommon problem: when I fold and close the phone (from its very impressive full screen) it shuts off. I mean, it powers down completely and the only way to access the phone is to turn it on and go through the power-on protocol. This means, I now must use my phone as a tablet, unless I am willing to go through the 2-3 minute power-on process each time I close the phone. I am passed warranty and repairs here in Mexico are somewhat problematic AND, how can you not have your phone for the days required for it to be repaired, a cost, I have been told, also appears to be steep... So, I have decided to switch from the foldable phones (which are beautiful) and I've ordered the S24 Ultra. I do hope the transition to a small screen won't be too much of a disappointment. Then again--to not have your phone work is a pretty serious disappointment in itself.    Thank you for the fair assessment of the S24 Ultra. By the way (oh, can yammer so) I have extensive high-quality photography gear. That said, the convenience of have my always-available phone/camera has allowed me to take innumerable high-quality photographs I would not have had were it not for my phone. The photos I have taken with my Samsung phones, given the nature of the equipment, have been and continue to be superb. I do run them through Snapseed software, and, again, given the nature of the equipment, I couldn't be happier. ... Thanks for allowing me space to ramble.

In general the photos look pretty similar and hard to differenciate, but in that 3rd one spotted something that happens with Samsung's portraits, and is that obviously, they dont have the physical capacity to make that depth of field naturally, so they hape to fake it, and it does a great job in general, but some times you can see some artifacts it makes like putting one random leaf in focus, some imperfections in the edges, and not realizing that the subject has parts where you can see the background, like your glasses, and when that happens it doesnt blur that part.

At this point, a professional camera is better in that, for professional use, when you want to edit the photo not just a bit. With a phone you can can get pretty much close, but doesnt let you thaaat much space for correction as it does with a real camera, it loses so much detail when you try to brighten dark parts or darken bright parts.

Nearly every item you buy that has glass in it has a coating, and that is what is scratching. The increased strength is more about impact resistance. The coatings are what provide things like fingerprint resistance, reduced glare etc.

The only one I found that could replace my iPhone is the Pixel 8 Pro. I didn't find the same problems with it that I find with Android smartphones. The voice command works perfectly (unlike other Androids where, for some reason, I can never get the voice command to work on the Gboard keyboard). Plus, when setting up a new phone, you can have an exact copy of your old Pixel, just like you do with a new iPhone.

This isn't the case with Samsung, etc., where you have to put all the apps back into folders again, reorganize your folders, etc.

In the end, I found the photo and video quality to be less good than on the iPhone, so I kept my iPhone 15 Pro Max and returned the Pixel. But now, I'm looking forward to the Pixel 9 Pro XL. I'll be very happy to see Google reclaim its crown as the king of photography.

They have the means and the talent; I don't know what's missing for them to achieve it.

Having a disability, voice command allows me to write very quickly without getting exhausted, so for me, it's essential. Moreover, I don't understand why, when copying data from an old Android smartphone to a new one, you don't get an exact copy of what you had on the old one. You have to reorganize everything, recreate folders from scratch, etc. It's a basic feature, and Android is advanced enough to have this kind of functionality. I'll never understand.
